  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering Control Act)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. State Statutes:\n- Most states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- These typically mirror federal regulations and provide additional enforcement mechanisms\n\n3. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Impose penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\n4. Primary Regulatory Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering activities by establishing comprehensive legal frameworks and enforcement mechanisms.",
